A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase like the vertebral column of a dinosaur, and the balconies are cracked fish mouths.
This is Barcelona's Casa Batlló by Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi.
From the local inhabitants the house with its organic shapes got the nickname & quot; Bone House & quot;.
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile chips and mosaics, the scale-like façades and omnipresent soft lines - all these are characteristics typical of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The façade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures that recall nature and creatures.
Only on closer inspection do you notice that everything is controlled by geometry, rhythm, and well thought out order.
At night, the whole façade is even more three-dimensional, dramatic, and the special lighting adds to the brightness of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate forms dominate the interior of the house as well.
Wavy shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and moldings.
House Batlló is located in the Eixample district, on the busy shopping street of Number 43, Passeig de Grácia. It is the result of a renovation of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
Reconstruction took two years to complete and was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old one and building an entirely new one, but ultimately agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló apartment building was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked together with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on this drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of reality were created, and also the use of mosaics on the façade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also contributed to the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was also involved in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá in Güell Park, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Already shortly after its completion the house got the nickname & quot; bone house & quot; from the local inhabitants for its organic forms.
Others called it 'quot;' due to its special window opening mechanism, while others called it the 'quot; gaping house'.
It is also said that at the very top of the building there is a picture of the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But also other sculptural elements symbolise hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed for the house a central heating system unique for the time, with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree tilt already looks a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was not at all deterred by these.
Before building started, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he gave about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city fathers were so appalled by the outcome that they demanded redress.
Among other things, the councillors also clashed on the fact that the building with its pillars even encroached on the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, quite the opposite - just fifteen days after the district requested it to do so, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two tallest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted them.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon. On the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the flat.
The ground floor has been leased to a jewellery shop.
The entire six-story building traverses a set of stairs leading up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the rebuild all right angles and straight lines have been eliminated and replaced with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí, however, also worked with a modern concept of the interconnection of spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors, allowing a larger company to chat comfortably, without sacrificing some intimacy for more intimate conversations.
In addition to a new façade, Gaudí's reconstruction also gave the house a rather unusual roof and two additional floors.
Gaudí's play on light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles covering the courtyard and the courtyards.
Play of these two colors gives maximum light to all floors of the house.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, which was included in Unesco's World Heritage List in 2005, can be visited by anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and sumptuous apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the famous creator's 150th birthday.
When it was realized that this is a fairly lucrative business, it retained the tours, and even extended them to other common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
The price for a visit to the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 Euro. Students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the admission fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Whoever wants to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its little dragon turrets should try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
