A longer index finger than ring finger means a lower risk of getting cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of getting prostate cancer.
That is the surprising finding of a study published Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is said to be related to levels of the male hormone testosterone.
& quot; Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixty, & quot; said study co-author Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if genetic or other risk factors are present, such as family health stresses, Ms. Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and her colleagues in Britain tracked more than 1,500 patients suffering from prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men at the same time.
In more than half of the study's participants, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was found as for 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, for men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and for men up to the age of sixty it decreased by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which form as early as prenatal age, evidently reflects the different levels of sex hormones the child was exposed to in the uterus.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
Previous research found that it is precisely the testosterone that accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was vaguely aware of this study, yet he considers that the relationship between finger length and cancer risk has not yet been fully established.
