Can courtesy join the disconnect?
After a campaign of swear words and negativity, little civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of real two-party cooperation, or a moment of illusion, before quickly returning to the parties' fight in the capital?
The Tuesday meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders failed to yield a breakthrough on the big issues to deal with during the so-called & quot; lame duck session & quot;, the session at the end of a government period when no decisions are made.
After all you hear, it was neither a courteous discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The president's deficit commission public meeting on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the policy differences that persist between members.
It appears to be clear that a close interaction over a period of months produces a mutual respect that masks the ideological chasm that continues to divide members from each other.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has begun.
Both sides are now in a test phase - one demanding from the other sign of willingness to cooperate and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and voters' patience after another partisan warfare.
Thus, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its evaluation by the attendees was limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere prevailing in the past two years.
Whether it's about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November election, at least for a short time, gave Washington a soft ride.
& quot; No question, the tone has changed & quot;, said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the & quot; Ethics and Public Policy Center & quot;.
& quot; This is inescapable after-elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die away again.
And that's good. & quot;
On some issues, especially those on the agenda of the & quot; lame duck session & quot;, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one advocates that.
Both sides want to find a way to get some or even all of them, be it temporarily or permanently.
Similarly, a compromise on the increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe that the favored tax cuts for the rich are being cut while denying assistance to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's White House meeting, there is a growing optimism that one can agree on these issues during the & quot; lame duck session & quot; while also ratifying the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Insitution warns that a successful cooperation on pressing issues of the lame duck session & quot; does not necessarily lead to a durable cooperation of parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a phase of non-match is more likely, maybe even unavoidable.
& quot; After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation & quot;, he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
& quot; I see much that is happening from today until 2012, as a prelude, or shadow boxing, for the main 2012 event & quot;, he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the presentation of the new Republican majority in the White House and with the tea party voters who were conducive to their formation.
However concerned Republican leaders may be about playing too high a game of poker, they know they have to try to keep their promises to cut government spending and repeal health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the first reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, as well as raising the retirement age and lowering government spending.
Vice-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington, and, according to their own assessment, have been pushing so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the commission to make their plan the official recommendation, and they fight hard to even get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is found in the elected representatives of the body, because, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise in financial issues.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first fight will take the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans will challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes, and the health care system, followed later by a period of major bipartisan cooperation.
What's going to lead to this change?
The public opinion.
It has been proven that, despite the partisanship of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is doomed to losing will have to change course and seek the compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than in the mid-1990 "s, and they seem to be a bigger ideological chasm between Obama and congressional Republicans than it was at the time between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as just a prelude to a much more consequential election in 2012.
Viewed in this way, the courtesy worn this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will require much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator in the questions that still divide the two from each other.
