& quot; He was a good leader and he cared about his people & quot; said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years.
Because of his brutality during Khmer Rouge rule known as the & quot; the butcher & quot;, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwest Cambodia, where he has built hospitals and bridges, developed the infrastructure and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge's capitulation to the government, longtime supporters are being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a school textbook that, for the first time, tells the history of Khmer Rouge to children of former soldiers.
And in July, a UN-Cambodia Joint Tribunal for the first time convicted a former member of the Khmer Rouge when it sentenced the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these developments, fears grew among Khmer Rouge veterans Alnlong Veng, complicating their efforts at reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodian society.
& quot; There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything, & quot; said Chhang Youk, head of the Documentation Center of Cambodia, an independent organization researching the regime.
& quot; For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil. & quot;
& quot; It splits even families. & quot;
During Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died from disease, overwork or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-Ied government in 1979, the regime's remnants and its military fled to Cambodia' s border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerilla war from their base in the west of the mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok raised the next generation in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, resulting in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had not yielded, was arrested in 1999 by government forces near the Dangrek Mountains.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh prison, awaiting his trial.
When their patrons stopped protecting them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled to the crushing poverty of rural Cambodia, and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Even if a few elite Khmer Rouge officials kept their local government posts because they were laying down their weapons, the rank-and-file soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
& quot; These people have benefited very little from the capitulation & quot; said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng
& quot; You are anchored in the regime's utopian agrarian ideology. & quot;
& quot; You grew up without any professional knowledge. & quot;
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Rhmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlang Veng, before settling in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
& quot; Life Under the Khmer Rouge was good & quot;, he said.
