& quot; Cambodia lives in peace and stability, she said.
& quot; If there were no more pursuits, there would be war here. & quot;
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court indicted more suspects, although experts and historians discuss this.
& quot; Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past & quot;, he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
& quot; reconciliation with Khmer times means gathering together the broken pieces & quot;, he said.
& quot; It is our duty to put these broken pieces together so that like everything can understand. & quot;
The center created the first government-approved textbook about the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page & quot; history of the Democratic Cambodia & quot;.
