Red Bull wins F1 with a Siemens secret weapon
The trolleys are enhanced in real-time using software.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history has been marked by surprises and successes in this exquisite universe of speed.
Initially nobody paid attention to the newcomer, and despite its steeply ascending trajectory during the last few seasons, everyone was counting on the victory of Fernando Alonso's Ferraris for the final sprint last November.
Without wishing to detract from the abilities of the German pilot and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of the Renault engine, the & quot; secret weapon, which Multi Siemens put in Red Bull hands, thus creating a winning team, has become a legend.
In reality, this is a powerful software for simulating processes. The German company launched it in 2007 for purposes other than car racing.
This informatics program, known as PLM, was used for developing assembly chains in factories around the world, power plants, and high-precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce or simulate a product or process faithfully before it is actually built, in order to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's cameras, Sukhoi' s aircraft, and Nissan's most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industry division, explains that with the use of this software in the Formula 1 - factory Red Bull & quot; in a few hours, almost in real-time & quot; can design and execute the changes and improvements that are detected on the races and during the tests.
Russwurm points out that in 1992, there were an average of ten technicians working in the race stables. They could introduce a maximum of three or four improvements in a season.
Today, in Red Bull's team, there are 180 highly skilled young people. Using powerful computer systems, they perform analyses and all sorts of changes to the race car.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software was capable of analysing and improving all the components of Red Bull's race cars, except for the engine for which only Renault claims to be responsible.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be transferred from the simulator's virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced production equipment and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limit that is set to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million that a Formula 1 team is allowed to spend on its races in a season.
Red Bull has set up its high-tech factory for designing and manufacturing its race cars in a location 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits - especially from journalists - are very limited.
All that is happening there is Top Secret.
The workforce includes 580 people, including the two pilots, World Champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull's true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the newest world champion Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts into service for its participation on the racetracks, there are other protagonists whose support is priceless and whose notoriety is zero.
The plant's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, emphasized that five years ago, it was still possible to say that advances in R & amp; E for racing cars contributed 50 percent to victory, with pilots responsible for the rest.
Today share values have changed. Technology accounts for 85 percent of the success, while the pilots' contribution is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computerized because they are unpredictable gladiators & quot;.
