Zapatero and Germany's Red Line
Berlin has decided to keep the euro, but at the same time imposed conditions for the whole of the European Union.
Tensions in the markets have triggered a dual response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has proposed new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, regulation of temporary work agencies, or the cancellation of the 426 euro assistance for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the management of the Barajas and El Prat airports, and 30 percent of the state's lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of the government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former head of the government, Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for evoking the current crisis.
How are these operations to be understood?
Let's face it, Merkel' s position is not a mistake in her public relations.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is adopting a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, one that conflicts with the maintenance of the traditional traditions of a majority of its partners.
Faced with the resistance in Europe, one begins speculating in Germany about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the re-introduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third: a re-shaping of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishing countries that exceed the targets; possibly the default of some countries, as well as extending the cost of potential adjustment to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been looming for some time. So there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created deficit incentives, and the German government pulled off a constitutional reform of its own to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
This was the first sign of the drifting apart between what Germany thought was necessary (strict fiscal plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second signal was sent to the central European country, as Merkel painfully delayed the decision to save Greece.
At that time this was heavily criticized. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against a bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel is coming out again with a clear position. She is calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements in order to allow the rescue of a country while at the same time obliging the private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position was interpreted as anti-European, as it propelled the Ireland crisis and everything that followed.
But your proposal, albeit somewhat sweetly, was accepted. In the next few months, we will participate in the reform of the European Union that will enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line which it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - the old functionality of the Euro will not exist anymore after this date.
2013 will be the year a new currency is born, in which the offending countries will be severely punished, can be forced to declare insolvent, and in this case the private sector will have to bear some of the costs.
Germany is showing us that we need to embark on a tough course of growth, with high savings and investment rates, consumption moderation, improvement in productivity and competitiveness, as well as positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as led by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad at not understanding it.
It's not just about bringing the state deficit down to three per cent by 2013.
Demands are much tougher.
And the worst we could do in these conditions is to cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will pass in more serenity.
And that we will make use of the opportunities we are given until the spring of 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this well, and his dual announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big business last Saturday, and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in one's own home has made its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like that would change anything about it.
Among the possibilities considered is that we would have to leave the euro area stuffed with little serious countries, not to be excluded.
In this case, Germany could still tell us it has warned us.
Sport and rule circumvention
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show ingenuity, but not a willingness to bypass a sanction.
The exclusion allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the 23 November match against Ajax in the Champions League caused a lot of ink to be spilled over whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether possibly both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As everyone knows, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already won decisively) and played several fouls for the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed sanction on the next league game against the Auxerre, thus entering the next phase of play without any cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club' s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate that has arisen around the case is due to a team of Real Madrid football club (who pretended nobility and honor in their anthem and on other occasions punished their players for similar incidents) playing the lead role in it, and due to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is not explicitly prohibited by the statutes, contravenes the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions constitute rule circumvention. In fact, this procedure adheres to the statutes of sport, but seem to circumvent their meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused by the sportsspirit should be investigated.
The sportsspirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect not jeopardized by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the offending players from taking any undue advantage from the counter team. Again, that was not done.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we usually understand to false play or rule circumvention, because the circumvention of the rule was n 't secretly performed to avoid a sanction, but rather it should be as conspicuous as possible, so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and joyfully accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offender drew from the deliberate fouls.
Here it should be emphasized that the rival was neither placed in a less favorable position nor advantages were demanded for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not then have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players start the next game phase of the Champions League without any cards, which could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-run, to a certain degree of an uncertain advantage, since the team could eventually exit as well. Also, with this approach players get a sanction and move on to the second card cycle, where they are eliminated due to accumulation with one card less than in the first cycle.
This makes it not so clear whether it is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices are not directed against sportsmanship, which includes strategic choices to maximize the benefits of the regulations.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they rather chose when to submit to it.
You made a strategic choice, without dodging or fleeing from a penalty.
Although the boundary between Inventive Gift and Rule Environment is blurred, I believe that this matter is a clear case of Inventive Gift.
I get the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: Because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the way the rule transfer was provoked.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
