China Maintains Its Goals to Reduce Greenhouse Gases
The representative of China declared at COP16 that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce trace carbon emissions, and that it would maintain its offer of reducing 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the country's representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations World Climate Change Summit (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country has made tremendous efforts to reduce carbon footprints and transform its industry.
He said that over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its goals, but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He explained that China's strategy on climate change is structured around four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building, and pilot program support.
Progress has been made on all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new energy bill, which includes goals on reducing emissions of gases, he said.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, the authorities of the states had worked together with those of the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of saving energy, using energy effectively and reducing emissions.
In addition, he explained, some multi-year plans have already been started or completed, both those funded by the Chinese government and those that received money from other countries.
For example, he was referring to the Effective Use of Energy program, which was introduced in the last five years and had received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and from private hands.
There is also a provincial-level project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving bulbs, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, government scientific adviser on climate change issues in this country, confirmed that China's efforts are far greater than is commonly thought.
He pointed out that the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons per person. China is responsible for a nine percent overall contribution to environmental pollution.
It is also making unprecedented strides in energy usage. Energy efficiency has increased by twenty percent over the past five years, and another is due to happen by 2020, he said.
