Green but outright sceptical.
The Quebec consumer has little confidence in the major players of sustainable growth, but neither do the labeled brands or the eco labels that are supposed to guide his or her choice.
Pity, though it bathes in a media-savvy universe teeming with information in favor of more responsible consumption: the responsible consumption barometer has a lack of credible information to complain about, an inadequacy that turns itself out to be a brake on its engagement, as the first reading held yesterday showed.
Although they advanced consumption of the so-called socially acceptable products in 2010, Quebeckers still seem to have little credit for those who try to sell them.
Two thirds of Quebec's population admits to not really believing in companies' environmental commitment any more than they do green corporate advertising, according to the measurement instrument elaborated by the responsible consumer center at Sherbrooke University.
Another finding: half of consumers doubt the trustworthiness of the official certificates attached to the supposedly fair products, as well as the credibility of the products and brands that declare themselves environmentally conscious, according to the barometer.
In the same pattern, politicians' discourse on this subject is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebec's population.
The information regarding responsible consumption seems nonetheless important for stimulating this consumer segment, which is currently populated by approximately only one third of Quebec's consumers.
In fact, emptiness and the dubious nature of information dampened the zeal of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the barometer after the higher price of the products.
In addition, a third of Quebeckers are suspicious of the stated performance of the green products and services they are trying to get hold of.
According to another communication, more than half of the consumers had already changed their habits in 2010, and predominantly changed the brand of one or more products in order to express their conviction.
According to the barometer, 61% of them had preferred shopping at their district's merchants and favored buying food grown in their region.
Greener and Responsible - the eco-conscious consumption index had reached a 64 of the maximum score of 100 this year - the Homo consuus of Quebec loves to present itself as the king of recycling, trying to reduce the traces left in the environment by being concerned about animal welfare.
However, the social and environmental consciousness still seems to stop in front of its car, according to the barometer: just 28% of Quebeckers reported to have used public transportation in 2010, or to have preferred the ride-sharing center to demonstrate their ecological interest.
