Worldwide Lighting Renewal Plan
The UN proposed yesterday in Cancun a plan to renew lighting for homes, trade and industry in 100 countries, with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions (CFC) equivalent to nearly one third of the additional reduction that will have to be realized to stabilize Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun, to compensate for the absence of industrialized countries' mandatory reduction commitments.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem, in the form of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of CFC emitted to the Earth as a result of lighting, would be avoided if the white-hot bulbs, which so far represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent, or better yet, light-emitting diodes (LED).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
