Vengeful hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks Affair has two meanings.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is only a scandal in Sinner Hypocrisy, which governs the relationship between the states, the citizens, and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at an international level, and gives a foretaste of the regression-dominated future.
But let us go ahead by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that any intelligence service file (of any nation) is composed exclusively of newspaper cuttings.
The & quot; extraordinary & quot; American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits throw up nothing more than what one could read for months anyway in any journal (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gadhafi' s alarmingly caricatured profile provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches for a long time.
The rule according to which the secret dossiers may consist only of news already known is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
When you go into a library dedicated to esotherical publications, you will realize that each work (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars, or the Cross of the Roses) exactly repeats what has already been written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish any research (yet because he does not know where to find news about the non-existing), but because those who are dedicated to occult texts believe in nothing other than what they already know and what they have already learned.
This is also the Dan Brown success mechanism.
Likewise the secret file.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) is also the chief of intelligence (otherwise, he could be whatever, for example, editor at Libération), who only considers as true what he acknowledges.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as those that Newsweek had already published the week before.
So why has there been such fuss about the disclosures of these dossiers?
On one page, these state what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of World War II and since then also the Heads of Government can call each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few minor representation tasks, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore this.
Nevertheless: the fact of repeating it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy in a bad light.
In second place, the idea that an x-factor hacker can tap the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world carries the considerable blow to the prestige of the state department.
What's more, the scandal is less about the victims and more about the & quot; executioner & quot;.
But let us be concerned with the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's day, all power could be concentrated like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of its subjects.
Orwell's prophecy could have turned out to be perfectly accurate since then, where you could control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel you visited, the chosen highway, and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
If, however, one considers what is happening today that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape a hacker's control, then the control process ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the citizen's Avenger - can discover the secrets of power.
How, however, can a power that is no longer able to keep its own secrets hold?
It's true, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi' s or Merkel's character is basically a secret free of secrets, since it exposes the public sphere; but to reveal, in the style of WikiLeaks, that Hillary Clinton' s secrets were empty secrets is to strip them of any power.
WikiLeaks did not wrong Sarkozy or Merkel, but Clinton and Obama did.
What will the consequences of this insult inflicted upon such a mighty power be?
It is obvious that states will not put any reserved information online any more in the future - that would be tantamount to a notice being stuck on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies it is futile to hope to be able to keep confidential reports about telephone secret.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a leader of state has moved away in an airplane and contacted one of his or her colleagues.
How could we maintain private and only-certain-ears-only relationships in the future?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and romanticism, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, moving in a secret manner diligently on uncontrollable marching routes, carrying their messages nowhere else but in the bare memory, and furthermore hiding the little written information they got in the shoe sales.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that today, technology is advancing like a cancer, namely backwards.
A century after the wireless telegrapher revolutionized communication, the Internet is reconstructing a telegrapher with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) videocassettes had enabled the filmmakers to scout a film tape by tape, by allowing one to spool from back to front and reveal all the secrets of the montage, while the (numeric) CDs nowadays allow nothing more than to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, in macro proportions.
High-speed trains take three hours to travel from Rome to Milan, whereas flying requires three-and-a-half hours including the transfer.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to the car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times the press tried to understand what kind of secrets were forged between the embassies.
Currently, it's the embassies demanding confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France whitewashes its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen accord, it is time to investigate the fulfilment of the fast-solved financing promises (also called the & quot; Fast Start & quot; or premature financing) realized by developing countries.
And already the rough French goodies have been revealed.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed to allocate 30 billion dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged €7.2 billion over three years. France has pledged €1.26 billion (or €420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to fast-start funding: detailed procedure report of its member states, press conference, big side events, brochure distribution.
The Transparency operation is noteworthy, and grade prized for its real value: the developing countries and civil society would like to see all developed countries doing the same on the same precision level.
The EU announces to have released 2.2 billion Euros in 2010, which puts it on the right track to repay its commitment of 7.2 billion Euros in 2012.
But if you look at the detail, things are a little bit more complicated.
This money, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, was to be a & quot; new and additional to & quot; in order to ensure that an extra effort was made without prejudice to Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately there is no consensus on what & quot; means new and additionally & quot;.
While the EU Commission had proposed a harmonization, certain member states, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark they consider best.
The EU Commission, for example, has chosen itself as the benchmark for 2009: the international financing will be maintained, adding 150 million over three years to & quot;'s funding for & quot; Fast-Start & quot;.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of Official Development Assistance.
In return, France was of the opinion that the financing of & quot; all new projects & quot; of 2010 was & quot; new and additionally & quot;.
In other words, there are no benchmarks for the amount spent in the preceding year, or at the global level of Official Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total sum of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France pretends to honour its commitment regarding the amount of new and additional & quot; funding.
Another key element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their arithmetic mode.
Some, such as France, find 1 borrowed €as the equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often projects tied to emission containment based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro you collect as the equivalent of one euro donated... Moreover, only the cost of the loan should be counted as a commitment for the country providing the funding (ie; the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in the sense except the following consideration: it respects & quot; its obligation of 420 million euros by taking 91.5% loan (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) 36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document for self-assurance.
France is the only EU country to make a large-scale loan application.
Germany claims 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) fulfil 100% of their obligations with donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its obligations, France gives just 10 cents, and understands that to be a comparable amount.
Nice hocus-pocus!
All in all, France operates with a double swindle in its near-start financing: to one part with an evolution of the action over time, and to the other part with the reality of the financial expenditure.
France manages to be credited with having spent 420 million new & quot; million and extra quot; million in accordance with its promises, saving 36.1 million euros in the process.
Manipulating the Treasury (since it seems as though it was Bercy who did the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once inside the EU (why are the other member states continuing to donate when it is enough to borrow anyway?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived after all...
The chapter of early funding only a small question on a relatively short time relative to the entirety of climate discussions.
But it could be the drop too many in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is imperative to learn its lesson from this first year of premature funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting type for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of compensatory justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could bring to the front the discussions on the subject of long-term financing (another, crucial issue, and currently discussed): one cannot escape the question of & quot; transferability, & quot; or the accounting of its loans.
France could change its position to be just as progressive on the issues of dispute as it is on other things.
So the hope is based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about the fast-start of France, and its vision of & quot; transferability & quot; as well as the use of loans, would by nature lift the international confidence base necessary for further discussion.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years of age takes 81 different chemical substances during the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Générations Futures Association (former movement for the protection of rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which declares that its results, given the small number of samples analyzed, do not represent a statistically significant value, but are an illustration of the problematic issues & quot; is dealing with, had purchased the foods usually consumed in four, plus one snack, from the supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five pieces of fresh fruit and fruit, three dairy products, and 1.5 liters of water a day - were studied as well as nibbles from laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals, and other pollutants.
The plate balance is staggering: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possible or likely to be carcinogenic, and five classified as safe carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptors, according to studies of several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Center.
& quot; Even if, in the approximate totality of cases, the legal limits are not exceeded for each chemical, individually taken substance, it is nevertheless very well taken from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is possibly exposed to carcinogenic substances, or substances with endocrine disrupting factors, is worrying, notes the Association.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the possibly carcinogenic residues and three that have been proved to be safe to use as carcinogens, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, for which the study found traces of an insecticide strictly prohibited in the EU.
There were also the mincer steak, the tuna from the tin, even the baguette and chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances.
For tap water, the analyses have brought the presence of nitrates and chloroform to light.
At dinner, the salmon steak was at the most & quot; abundant with 34 chemical residues detected, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this & quot; cocktail of harmful substances & quot; for the consumer & quot; is likely to be undervalued & quot;, according to the study.
For its part, the & quot; Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts & quot; (EE-LV), in view of the urgency of the situation, has proposed to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the & quot; increasing frequency of civilization diseases.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) regarding the presence of residues had identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables being consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
